What's it like to have a period as a trans man? New Delhi-based @kabir.maan shares his experience.  

This Menstrual Hygiene Day, in partnership with @anuragchauhanofficial, Founder - Humans for Humanity, we are shedding light on the plight of menstruating trans men. They are often not included in conversations about periods, resulting in the fear of being harassed in public washrooms, and, mostly, emotional trauma. Many even lack the resources to invest in proper menstrual hygiene care. 

Watch to know more. 

#HumansWhoPeriod #MyCarmesi #CarmesiPads #MenstrualHygiene #MenstrualHygieneDay2022 #MHD2022 #Periods #Menstruation #DegenderMenstruation

Even as the world slowly challenges the stigma attached to menstruation, a crucial aspect remains unchanged. We still associate women and girls with menstruation - starting from the way we speak about it to the way period products are marketed only keeping women in mind. In doing so, we leave out a community that also bleeds but does not identify as women - trans men.

As a result, they feel shame about their menstruating bodies while battling with society - always scared of being bullied or beaten. They are also frightened to speak up about the emotional trauma that they face regarding their gender identity. 

This Menstrual Hygiene Day, in partnership with @anuragchauhanofficial, Founder - Humans for Humanity, we are shedding light on the plight of these menstruating trans men and why introducing gender-neutral toilets is the need of the hour - because everyone deserves access to safe menstrual hygiene management!

We urge you to share this video as much as possible, using #HumansWhoPeriod. Further, you can opt to volunteer with Humans for Humanity under their WASH project to help spread awareness about menstrual health and hygiene. 

#HumansWhoPeriod #MyCarmesi #CarmesiPads #MenstrualHygiene #MenstrualHygieneDay2022 #MHD2022 #Periods #Menstruation #DegenderMenstruation

In the cisnormative world that we live in, menstruation is heavily branded as a female-only phenomenon. 

But, not everyone who bleeds identifies as a woman. 

Because there are other people, like trans men, who also menstruate. Trans men are those who are born female at birth but identify as men. And, unfortunately, most conversations about menstruation leave trans men out. As a result, they are scared to talk about the emotional trauma they face surrounding menstruation. They are not comfortable talking about their menstruating bodies, all the while lacking the resources to do so.

This #MenstrualHygieneDay (May 28), we intend to start a conversation around degendering menstruation. Because #HumansWhoPeriod deserve to be treated with dignity. No matter their gender, every menstruator deserves access to safe period management.

In partnership with @anuragchauhanofficial, Founder - Humans for Humanity, we will shed light on the emotional trauma, social stigma, and lack of resources and representation for all menstruators. Watch this space to know more.

#menstrualhygiene #menstruation #periods #menstrualhygieneday2022 #hygiene #transmen #transgender #MHDay2022 #degendermenstruation #health #MyCarmesi #CarmesiPads

Deciding when to sleep with your partner is a deeply personal choice that varies for everyone. It’s essential to feel emotionally connected and ensure both partners are comfortable with the decision. Trust and respect play a significant role, as does discussing expectations and potential implications, such as how it might affect the relationship. Safety is equally important—using protection and being aware of each other’s sexual health helps foster a responsible and caring connection. 

Ultimately, the right time is when both partners feel secure, valued, and aligned in their desires and intentions, without external pressure or expectations.

A couple of days ago, we received a DM that pointed out how rarely we talk about butt acne. That got us thinking: Why are discussions around butt acne so few and far in between?

Butt acne, or folliculitis, is surprisingly common and completely manageable with the right knowledge and care. Unlike traditional facial acne, butt acne often results from inflamed hair follicles caused by friction, sweat, bacteria, or even irritation from shaving.

If you’ve been struggling with these bumps, you’re not alone, and there’s no need to feel embarrassed. Your skin deserves consistent care, no matter where it’s located.

Save this post for later and share it with someone who might find it helpful!

#skincare101 #buttacne #selfcarematters #bodypositivity #healthyskin #folliculitiscare #skintips #skincarecommunity #MyCarmesi #CarmesiPads

latestPosts.caption:
For most of my life, my body didn’t feel like mine.
I still remember the first time someone commented on my weight. I was 10 years old, playing with my cousins, when an aunt casually said, “You shouldn’t eat so much; you’ll get fat.” At the time, I didn’t think much of it, but that small comment planted a seed; a seed that would grow into years of self-loathing and hatred.
As I got older, the comments didn’t stop.
“You’d look better if you lost a little weight.”
“Why don’t you try layering your clothes?”
“You’re pretty, but imagine how much prettier you could be.”
Each word hit like a thorn, pricking away at my self-esteem. By the time I was in high school, I couldn’t look in the mirror without criticizing myself.
Then one day, after years of avoiding mirrors, I caught a glimpse of myself in a window. I stopped. For the first time, I didn’t see what others had always pointed out. I didn’t see flaws. I saw tired eyes. I saw a body that had carried me through heartbreaks, sleepless nights, celebrations, and laughter so hard it left me breathless.
I saw a body that deserved love. That’s what I saw in my reflection that day; a body that had been waiting for my love all along.
I won’t lie; there are still hard days. Days when the voices of the past creep back in, whispering old criticisms. But now, I’ve learned to talk back. I remind myself that I’m more than a number on a scale or the size of my jeans. Bodies are different, and that’s okay. As long as I’m treating my body with care and focusing on my health instead of looks, I am enough.

So here’s my challenge to you: What’s one thing you love about your body today? Share it in the comments; I’d love to hear your story. 

Siddhi- Team Carmesi

The Taliban’s latest decree, banning windows in homes where women could be seen, is another grim reminder of their ongoing campaign to erase women’s visibility and agency. What they call "protecting" women is, in reality, the systematic stripping away of their rights and freedom.

From preventing women from working to restricting their movement and even silencing their voices, the Taliban’s oppressive measures aim to render women invisible in every sense. This isn’t just about a window; it’s about controlling every aspect of a woman's existence, erasing her humanity, and denying her basic rights.

This is not just their fight; it's ours too. Women’s rights are human rights. We cannot stay silent.

Ever came across those memes where a person does the simplest act of turning their head and voila! They pull a muscle! And, what are those memes about? Turning 30!

As exaggerated as it may sound in our 20s, it isn’t always that far from the truth once you reach the other side of 30! And women, especially, undergo a lot of bodily changes once the sun completes 30 revolutions since the day she’s born! This is why it’s so important to take care of your body with a healthy diet and a proper exercise routine.

So, swipe to check what happens to our bodies after 30! How has the 30s treated you? Tell us in the comments below!

To the women who are choosing a path less travelled,

We see you, we love you, and we celebrate you. Your decision to not have children doesn’t make you any less loving, any less whole, or any less worthy; it makes you, you. 

In a world that often judges and questions, you have the courage to live life on your own terms. You remind us that there is no single way to be a woman, and your choices are valid, powerful, and beautiful.

Your life is rich with meaning and purpose, shaped by your passions, your relationships, and your unique vision. Thank you for showing us the strength that comes from living authentically.

With love and pride,
Team Carmesi ❤️
